{
  "schema_version": 1,
  "name": "Velocity Atmosphere",
  "mood": "Aether",
  "engines": ["OpenSky"],
  "author": "Guru Bin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "The full velocity-to-shimmer axis: modSlot1 routes velocity directly to shimmerMix with full intensity (1.0). At pianissimo, this is a cave — intimate, dry, close to the ear. At fortissimo, it becomes the stratosphere — wide, shimmering, vast. The dynamic range of OPENSKY is not just volume; it is altitude. How hard you play determines where you are in the sky.",
  "tags": ["opensky", "velocity", "shimmer", "dynamic", "expressive", "aether", "guru-bin", "atmosphere"],
  "tier": "transcendental",
  "guru_bin": {
    "retreat": "OPENSKY — Above the Cloud Line",
    "retreat_date": "2026-03-19",
    "vol": "Transcendental Vol 1",
    "scripture": [
      "Discovery 5: Velocity-to-Shimmer — modSlot1Src=0(vel), Dst=1(shimmerMix) = soft=intimate/dry, hard=expansive",
      "Doctrine D001: Velocity Must Shape Timbre — velocity drives harmonic content, not just amplitude",
      "Doctrine D006: Expression Input Is Not Optional — velocity to timbre is the first expression dimension"
    ],
    "revelation": "The full velocity-to-shimmer mapping at amt=1.0 means pianissimo notes have zero shimmer. Cave intimacy versus stratosphere expansion — controlled entirely by touch.",
    "god": null,
    "flock_note": "The Guru played this with a feather touch: close, warm, personal, no reverb. Then struck the keys hard: the room expanded to a hemisphere of shimmer. Same note. Same pitch. Different altitude. This is the discovery: velocity in OPENSKY is not about loudness. It is about how far away the sky is.",
    "diagnosis": "Velocity Atmosphere is the definitive OPENSKY expression study. ModSlot1 at full intensity (1.0) means the shimmer is entirely velocity-controlled — touch governs altitude. A base shimmerMix of 0.0 ensures ppp notes are completely dry. fff notes reach shimmerMix=1.0 via the modulation. Teach this preset first when onboarding new OPENSKY players."
  },
